fr:mainmatter.html:p:
Without loss of generality, we may assume that f has an inverse 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen g,\epsilon ,\eta ,\chi \right \rparen \mathclose {}
. By Lemma , it suffices to argue that the type of inverses to f is a retract of a proposition; the type of inverses to f is in fact equivalent to the type of sections equipped with a coherent remainder:

By Lemma , it suffices to show that the type of sections to f is a proposition and that for every such section, the coherent remainder thereof is a proposition. The latter is Lemma , and the former follows from Lemma  by means of the retraction 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen g,\eta \right \rparen \mathclose {}
.

Without loss of generality, we may assume that f has an inverse 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen g,\epsilon ,\eta ,\chi \right \rparen \mathclose {}
. By Lemma , it suffices to argue that the type of inverses to f is a retract of a proposition; the type of inverses to f is in fact equivalent to the type of sections equipped with a coherent remainder:

By Lemma , it suffices to show that the type of sections to f is a proposition and that for every such section, the coherent remainder thereof is a proposition. The latter is Lemma , and the former follows from Lemma  by means of the retraction 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen g,\eta \right \rparen \mathclose {}
.

Given a function f\colon  A\to  B and a section g\colon  B\to  A witnessed by \epsilon \colon  f\circ  g = 1_{B}, we define the coherent remainder of 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen g,\epsilon \right \rparen \mathclose {}
 to be the following sum:

fr:mainmatter.fr:tex:
 \mathsf {coherentRemainder}_{f}
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen g,\epsilon \right \rparen \mathclose {}
 :\equiv  \mathchoice {\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \eta : g\circ  f \sim  1_{A}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \eta : g\circ  f \sim  1_{A}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \eta : g\circ  f \sim  1_{A}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \eta : g\circ  f \sim  1_{A}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}
 \mathsf {act}_{f}\circ  \eta  \sim  \epsilon  \circ  f

fr:mainmatter.html:p:
For any f\colon  A\to  B, it is evident that the type of inverses to f is (up to reassociation) precisely the dependent sum \mathchoice {\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \mathsf {section}\,f\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \mathsf {section}\,f\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \mathsf {section}\,f\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \mathsf {section}\,f\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}\mathsf {coherentRemainder}_{f}.

Let \sigma \equiv 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen g\colon  B\to  A,\epsilon \colon  f\circ  g =1_{B}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 be a section of a function f\colon  A\to  B. Then the coherent remainder of \sigma  is a proposition.

