}}{\scriptscriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{Bx} is a proposition.

We fix pairs 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen a,b\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 and 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen a',b'\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 in \mathchoice {\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{Bx}. By Definition  via Example , it suffices to exhibit identifications p\colon  a = a' and q\colon  p_* b = b'. These are given respectively by our assumptions that A and Ba' are propositions.

Let s \colon  B \to  A and r \colon  A \to  B be a pair of maps. A homotopy h \colon  r\circ  s \sim  1_{B} exhibits s as a section of r and r as a retraction of s. Together, 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen s,r\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 are referred to as a section-retraction pair.
